A Stargrave supplement of exploration and adventure, full of strange and wonderful alien worlds, species, and technologies.

Just beyond the rim of what was once &lsquo;civilized space&rsquo; lies the vast, colourful expanse of the Crokoan Nebula. Seeking their fortunes, bold independent crews press deep into this largely unexplored sector. But the Ravaged Galaxy is a dangerous place, and the threats that crews face are not limited to those found on a planet&rsquo;s surface. In fact, more independent crews meet their ends in the dark void of space than are wiped out in gunfights. Black holes, asteroid fields, and even the legendary space kraken can all destroy a ship and its crew. It takes a deft hand on the controls, a sharp eye on navigation, and a bit of wizardry with the engines to fly between the stars.

This supplement for&shy; Stargrave focuses on the ships that serve as the crews&rsquo; transports, strategic headquarters, and homes, including new upgrades, a damage system, and rules for crew assignments such as piloting, gunnery, and navigation. New powers, soldiers, technology, and backgrounds for captains and first mates help reinforce crews, while rules for space encounters &ndash; dangerous, interesting, and potentially profitable incidents &ndash; and five new scenarios bring them face to face with strange alien species and other terrifying dangers in weird and wonderful locations, from unexplored planets to the depths of space.&shy;

Goal of the game:
To be the first player to compose the Chef's Menu, consisting of 6 different courses (recognisable by the colour of the card frame), plus the bill card.
How to play? The game is played with open cards. After shuffling the cards the dealer does not deal any cards to the players, but places the covered deck in the centre of the table and turns over the first card, to start the discard pile and the game. 
In the event that the first card turned over is an action card, one continue to turn over other cards until you find a course (starter first course, second course, side dish, dessert and drink), after which the player to the left of the dealer starts the game (clockwise), choosing from the following possibilities:

     draw from the covered deck with the option to discard(discarding is optional);
     draw a useful range from the discard pile, without being able to never discard;
     play an action card from their own cards, without being able to draw or discard;
     discard a range from among one's cards without being able to draw.


